    %section
      %h1 What is a Fixed deposit?
      %p A Fixed Deposit (also known as Term Deposit) colloquially referred to as “FD” is a form of investment in which an investor deposits his money with a bank for a fixed period of time at a predetermined interest rate. After the term of the deposit ends, the investor gets the principal amount along with any outstanding interest.  Fixed deposits are also known as term deposits.
    %section
      %h1 What is the term of fixed deposits?
      %p Fixed deposit terms range from 1 week to 10 years. However, terms of 1 year, 2 years and 5 years are the most popular.
    %section
      %h1 When is interest paid?
      %p Investors have two options to receive interest:
      %p
        %b
          Regular basis:
        Investors can opt to receive interest on a regular basis. They further have an option to receive interest either on a quarterly basis or a monthly basis. The rate of interest offered on a monthly basis is less than that offered on a quarterly basis. In India however, interest is usually paid on a quarterly basis.
      %p
        %b
          Cumulative basis:
        Under cumulative basis, interest is calculated on a quarterly basis and interest earned is redeposited. The interest redeopsited earns interest too, thus fetching an investor higher returns than what he would stand to earn had he opted for interest to be received on a regular basis. To get an idea of difference in interest earned, we have a small illustration below. The amount deposited is Rs 1,00,000 for 2 years (8 quarters) at 10% interest p.a..
