    %section
      %h1 How risky are fixed deposits?
      %p Fixed deposits are extremely safe in general. Each fixed deposit investment in a bank is insured up to Rs. 1,00,000. This essentially means that even if the bank goes bankrupt, you are still certain to receive your entire amount upto Rs 1,00,000.  However, our editors think that it is better for small investors to invest in fixed deposits at nationalized banks such as SBI, Andhra Bank, Bank of India etc or high grade private banks such as ICICI Bank, HDFC Bank etc. Some co-operative banks have gone bust in the past and it is probably better for small investors to avoid this risk.
    %section
      %h1 What is the interest rate on fixed deposits?
      %p Returns on fixed deposit are typically less than those from bonds and shares. This is because fixed deposits are immune to market volatility, economic turmoil and offer assured returns. Interest rates offered on fixed deposits vary over time and are largely influenced by the actions of the RBI.  Over the last 10 years, returns of fixed deposits for a period of 1 year have varied from 4.00% (In 2003-2004) to 8.25% (in 2010-2011).
