    %section
      %h1 20 year performance of Fixed Deposits
      %p
        If we take a view of a period of 20 years (1992-2011), returns form fixed deposits have exceeded those from the share markets. In 1992, had we invested equal sums of Rs 10,000 in shares and fixed deposits, fixed deposits would be worth Rs 55,740 today while shares (Nifty)  would be worth Rs 45,676.
      .center_align
        %caption
          20 Year's comparison of Share Return vs Fixed Deposit Returns
      =image_tag  "investment_education/20years_stock_fixeddeposit_returns.png"
      %p
        However if we curtail the time period to 10 years (2002-2011), share market overwhelmingly outperforms fixed deposits. In 1992, had we invested an equal sum of Rs 10,000 in shares and fixed deposits, fixed deposits would be worth Rs 17,779 while shares would be worth a whopping Rs 51,856.
      .center_align
        %caption
          10 Year's comparison of Share Returns vs Fixed Deposit Returns
      =image_tag  "investment_education/10years_returns_graph.png"
      %p The above difference is because the share markets in India were stagnant between 1992 and 2002 and returned -11.92%. However after 2002 the share markets took off in a big way and returned 577.3% over the next 10 years.
    %section
      %h1 Tax aspects of Fixed Deposits
      %p The interest earned on fixed deposits is taxed at the same rate at which your regular income is taxed. i.e. If your income falls under 20% bracket (income between Rs 5 lakhs –  Rs 8 lakhs bracket),  interest earned would be taxed at 20%. Moreover if your interest income is more than Rs 1,00,000 the bank is required to deduct 10% as tax deducted at source (TDS).
      %p Fixed deposits deposited for a period of 5 years are eligible for exemption under Sec 80C (upto Rs 1,00,000). However the interest earned on these fixed deposit is subject to tax.
    %section
      %h1 Can I redeem my fixed deposits before maturity?
      %p Yes, you can redeem your fixed deposit at any time you like. However the interest rate you would earn would be the prevailing rate of the shortened period (prevailing at the time you first made your deposit). Example: You invested in a 5 years fixed deposit that fetched you 10.5% in 2010. Two years later because of some reason you are forced to break your fixed deposit. The interest rate you would then get is the rate that a 2 year fixed deposit would stand to earn had it been made in 2010.
      %p
        In addition to the reduced interest you are also liable to be charged a penalty for breaking your investment before maturity. This rate varies from bank to bank and can further be negotiated.
        Note: If you invest in a fixed deposit and claim tax benefit under 80C against it, you cannot break the fixed deposit before it matures.
    %section
      %h1 Editor’s take
      %p If you are investing more than Rs 1 lakh in fixed deposits, try to spread your investment across different banks with no single investment over Rs 1 lakh. By doing this, you are ensuring that in the worst case scenario even if banks go bust your savings are insured. If you are looking to invest in a fixed deposit from the perspective of tax saving under Section 80c, be double sure about it because your investment is locked for a period of 5 years.


